slaying for Dummies</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE CENTER START--><center> <br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Dragonslaying for Dummies</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> or, How to Kill Nagafen in 4 Easy Steps</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
</center><!--EZCODE CENTER END--><br>
<br>
<br>
Look folks, this isn't that hard.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Step 1: People</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
To kill big things like dragons, you need people. Not only do you need people, but you need the right kind of people - specifically those who play raid-friendly classes and are level 48-52. (Raid-friendly classes are warriors, monks, rogues, bards, clerics, wizards.) You also need a buff team - if you can get level 60s great, if not, don't sweat it. On your buff team you'll want 2 clerics, a shaman, an enchanter, a magician, and someone to cast junk (i.e. a druid or a ranger).<br>
<br>
These people need 3 things:<br>
1) A set of resistance gear that can push Magic Resistance (MR) and Fire Resistance (FR) to at least 75 unbuffed, regardless of how far this drops AC, INT, WIS, or any other stat that is normally important. Appendix A lists items that provide both of the needed resistances. See Appendix B for magic resistance and Appendix C for fire resistance.<br>
2) The ability to comprehend and follow instructions. The most twinked uber character, if unable to follow instructions and work as part of a team, is useless. Take instead a first-timer who is scared enough to pay attention, if you can.<br>
3) Confidence. Believing you can win is an important element needed to execute properly. If you think you're a loser, chances are you will be.<br>
<br>
So the first part of Step 1 is knowing what you want. Aim for 36 people in the fight, with at least half of those being the core classes listed above. Get the best buffers that you can.<br>
<br>
How do I find these people, you may ask? Well there are several tools at your disposal. First, ask in your guildchat to see who is interested and what characters they can provide. Next, check your friends list. Third, post on the boards here to get names of people interested. If you need to scrape up a few extras around raid time, you can always resort to /who all 48 52 &lt;class&gt; or something along those lines. Try not to shout for extras in Sol B or Lavastorm as this tends to undermine the confidence of your raiding party.<br>
<br>
Finding buffers should not be difficult. Run down the list of guilds who want Ragefires and ask for specific contributions (i.e., 'I need a high level enchanter for some good haste for my Naggy raid, can you send somebody?'). Don't bother people in raid zones, but anyone else is fair game. Even in the worst case situation, you can do just fine buffing with the folks you have already on the raid - it's not ideal, but will work - after all, we killed Naggy plenty even when the level cap was 50 and the best weapon available was a SSoY (8/24 procs ykesha, FYI for you spoiled post-Kunark EQers). Primals are great, ask Dagga to lend you his. (Professionals only - do not try this at home!)<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Step 2: Getting there</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Well, great! You've passed the first hurdle and raised an army to slay this dragon. Send out your druids and wizards to bring your army together at the druid ring in Lavastorm. Kiss the hindquarters of your CotHer should you be fortunate enough to have one along.<br>
<br>
Once assembled, or mostly assembled, it's time to make the march to the lair. Have everybody zone into Sol B (a few at a time so you don't crash the zone). Pair experienced people with the clueless so you don't lose too many folks on the difficult trek through the zone. Feel free to kill anything in your path... others may be hunting there, but you're going to slay a dragon, so they'll just have to deal with it while you pass through. Their convenience is not worth wasting the time of the 40ish people who are going to say hi to Nags. From the lavastorm entrance, it's through the center tunnel, make a left, go past the rock coming down from the ceiling, and make a right. This takes you to the place affectionately known as 'bat 1'. Go left out of this room. The next room is 'bat 2', and again you take the left exit. At the fork, head right and continue down the hall, killing any spiders you see, until you reach the edge of the lava.<br>
<br>
At this point it's wise to take some folks who know which way is up to wipe out the first set of fire giants, lest you lose a noob in the excitement. (Then again, if you have too many people, you might just want to decide to leave behind anyone dumb enough to get killed in the next room, so it can serve as a weeding-out process.) Screw levitation, just swim through the lava and place yourself on the ledge. Have your puller start grabbing giants and slaughter them. If you can't figure out how to kill the giants safely, cancel your account and learn golf.<br>
<br>
