<br>
Finally you have reached the lair. Don't forget to pull the giants out of the lair (hint: send a monk) before you set up for the final battle. You now have about 8 hours before respawn, but probably a good deal less before everyone falls asleep, so don't waste time.<br>
<br>
First thing to do is make groups. Make melee groups starting with bards and clerics, then add your warriors, monks, and rogues to those groups. Group the highest levels together - being equalitarian doesn't help your chances, so make the strongest groups you can then group up the weaker characters afterwards. If someone's feelings are hurt that you group them among the weaker characters, well that's just too damn bad, you're a raid leader not a social worker. While you are making groups, issue the order to don resistance gear. My melee groups look like this: bard cleric &lt;melee&gt;&lt;melee&gt;&lt;melee&gt;&lt;melee or alt healer&gt;. Bards are great but don't put more than one in a group. More than 1 cleric in a heavy melee group is OK if you have plenty of clerics (unlikely, as Naggy doesn't drop much cleric loot, and most clerics don't give a sh|t about Naggy until they're closing in on Ragefire). Try to have all melee with a cleric if possible, or with 2 druids/shamans.<br>
<br>
Once groups are made, it's buff time. This can be the most confusing and complex part of the process for beginners, so remind people to follow instructions closely and be patient. You will set up a buff line and call the groups one by one. Each person is to start at the beginning of the line and receive their buffs in the order designated. Once a person is fully buffed they are to camp out to a chat room - the first person whose buffs are complete is to make the room! Call it Nagafen-Torv for simplicity.<br>
<br>
The basic idea behind buffing for Naggy is to expect him to dispel you. Naggy dispels 3 buffs each time he releases his AE, so you don't want the good ones at the top. You set up the buffing order based on this concept.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Buffing</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
First, you have the dispeller - his role is to make sure each person who presents himself for buffing starts out with an empty buff list. Remind people that they will die a horrible and premature death if they do not get properly buffed.<br>
<br>
Next is one or more junk-buffers. 3-5 junk buffs per person is fine. Good junk buffs are see invisible, DMF, resist cold/poison/disease.<br>
<br>
After the junk buffs come shaman buffs. People can choose their own as they wish but no more than 3 per person. STA is the best choice, DEX is also good, and STR and AGI can be OK.<br>
<br>
Next will be cleric #1, who will cast the best Symbol available (but not Aegolism!).<br>
<br>
After that, the enchanter(s) will cast INT/WIS buffs if neccessary and either haste or clarity as appropriate.<br>
<br>
Then, cleric #2 casts Heroism, then an AC buff. Ideally you'll want the best AC buff available, but in the interests of time Armor of Faith is often the best overall choice. Incidentally, if you do choose AoF, a paladin can sit in as buffer for AC.<br>
<br>
Next in the list is resistances - order doesn't really matter, but you'll want fire and magic. If you have a spare 54+ druid around for Circle of Winter, and a spare 49+ enchanter for Group Resist Magic, those are best; if not, any resist magic and fire will do.<br>
<br>
Finally, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> as the person is camping out</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, the mage should cast his longest-lasting damage shield on the player.<br>
<br>
Each character should submit to this process until all players have been buffed and sent to chat.<br>
<br>
